  "dateModified": "2026-03-06",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Point of view is the position from which a narrative is told — who sees, who speaks, and what access the reader has to characters\u0026rsquo; thoughts and perceptions. It is among the most consequential choices a fiction writer makes, because it determines what the reader can know and how they know it.\nThe primary categories are:\nFirst person — the narrator is a character in the story, using \u0026ldquo;I.\u0026rdquo; The reader has access to the narrator\u0026rsquo;s thoughts but is limited to the narrator\u0026rsquo;s perception. What the narrator doesn\u0026rsquo;t know, the reader doesn\u0026rsquo;t know. What the narrator misunderstands, the reader must detect through other cues. Third person limited — the narrator is outside the story but filters perception through one character at a time. The reader sees the world as that character sees it, but the narrator can report it in language the character wouldn\u0026rsquo;t use. Third person omniscient — the narrator can enter any character\u0026rsquo;s mind and knows things no character knows. George Eliot\u0026rsquo;s narrators comment on society, history, and psychology beyond any character\u0026rsquo;s awareness. Second person — the narrator addresses the reader as \u0026ldquo;you,\u0026rdquo; which can create immediacy or estrangement depending on whether the reader accepts the identification. Gérard Genette refined point of view into two distinct concepts: voice (who speaks?) and focalization (who sees?) [@genette1980]. A story can be narrated by one character but focalized through another — the narrator tells us what someone else perceives. This distinction clarifies cases that the traditional categories blur: a first-person narrator recounting events they didn\u0026rsquo;t witness, or an omniscient narrator who temporarily restricts perception to one character\u0026rsquo;s viewpoint.\n",
